<span class="displaytext"><b> <u>fact: governor (candidate last) closed a nearly $3 billion budget gap without raising taxes.</u> </b> <p><b>governor (candidate last) closed the nearly $3 billion shortfall without tax increases.</b> "when (candidate full) became governor of massachusetts in 2003, the state had a budget gap of almost $3 billion and was losing thousands of jobs a month. in mr. (candidate last)'s four-year tenure, the deficit was eliminated without raising the sales tax or the income tax, and since the labor slump hit bottom in december 2003, the state has gained 81,000 jobs." (pam belluck, "(candidate last) candidacy puts massachusetts economy in spotlight," <em>the new york times</em>, 3/16/07) </p><p><b>club for growth: governor (candidate last) "imposed much-needed fiscal discipline on a very liberal massachusetts legislature."</b> (the club for growth, "(candidate full)'s record on economic issues," press release, 8/21/07) </p><p><b>- to close the budget gap, governor (candidate last) forced the legislature to pass "tremendous spending cuts."</b> "governor (candidate last) receives credit for actual spending in fy 2003, even though he entered office halfway into the fiscal year, because of the tremendous spending cuts he forced down the legislature's throat in january of 2003. facing a $650 million deficit he inherited from the previous administration, (candidate last) convinced the unfriendly state legislature to grant him unilateral power to make budget cuts and unveiled $343 million in cuts to cities, healthcare, and state agencies. this fiscal discipline continued in 2004, in which (candidate last) continued to slash 'nearly every part of state government' to close a $3 billion deficit." (the club for growth, "(candidate full)'s record on economic issues," press release, 8/21/07) </p><p><b>- governor (candidate last) beat back "big-tax proposals" and chose instead "to erase deficits by hacking away at spending."</b> "what attracted many of these economists to the (candidate last) team was the former governor's success, in a liberal state, of beating back big-tax proposals and instead choosing to erase deficits by hacking away at spending." (kimberley a. strassel, op-ed, "tax talk," <em>the wall street journal</em>, 3/30/07) </p><p><b>fees only accounted for a small percent of the closure of the nearly $3 billion budget gap.</b> "(candidate last) campaign spokesman eric fehrnstrom said some of the fees that kicked in during (candidate last)'s first year had been approved before he became governor. ... 'when governor (candidate last) took office, he faced a $3 billion deficit,' fehrnstrom said. 'he balanced the budget primarily through spending cuts and reforms. fee increases accounted for approximately 10 percent of the solution, and they were not broad-based by any means.'" (steve leblanc, "(candidate last) oversaw millions in fee hikes as massachusetts governor," <em>the associated press</em>, 8/28/07) </p><p><b>massachusetts citizens for limited taxation executive director barbara anderson gives governor (candidate last)'s fiscal record high marks.</b> "barbara anderson of the anti-tax group citizens for limited taxation gave (candidate last) higher marks. 'to us a fee is what a fee is and a tax is what a tax is,' she said. 'his support for the income tax rollback never wavered.'" (steve leblanc, "(candidate last) oversaw millions in fee hikes as massachusetts governor," <em>the associated press</em>, 8/28/07) </p><p><b> <u>fact: governor (candidate last) "vetoed hundreds of millions of dollars in spending."</u> </b> </p><p><b>in the four budgets he signed, governor (candidate last) used the line-item veto or program reduction power in an attempt to cut spending by nearly $1 billion.</b> (office of governor (candidate full), "(candidate last) signs no new tax budget in time for new fiscal year," press release, 6/30/03; office of governor (candidate full), "governor (candidate full) signs $22.402b fiscal year 2005 'no new tax' budget," press release, 6/25/04; office of governor (candidate full), "governor (candidate full) signs into law $23.8 billion budget for fiscal year '06," press release, 6/30/05; office of governor (candidate full), "governor (candidate full) signs $25.2 billion fiscal year 2007 state budget," press release, 7/8/06) </p><p><b>- for all four of the fiscal-year budgets that crossed his desk, governor (candidate last) used the line-item veto power more than 800 times.</b> over the course of four budgets, governor (candidate last) made over 300 line-item reductions, 350 line-item eliminations and struck language 150 times. (chapter 26 of the commonwealth of massachusetts acts of 2003, governor's veto message, 6/30/03; chapter 149 of the commonwealth of massachusetts acts of 2004, governor's veto message, 6/25/04; chapter 45 of the commonwealth of massachusetts acts of 2005, governor's veto message, 6/30/05; governor (candidate full), memo to the senate and house of representatives of the commonwealth of massachusetts; fiscal year 2007 general appropriations act veto items: line item accounts, 7/8/06) </p><p><b>- beacon hill institute executive director david terck: "he vetoed hundreds of millions of dollars in spending."</b> wall street journal's paul gigot: "one of the criticisms of president bush is that's he's been unwilling to use his veto pen to reign in spending. was governor (candidate last) willing to use his veto pen to do that in massachusetts?" beacon hill institute executive director david terck: "he most certainly was. he vetoed hundreds of millions of dollars in spending." (fox news' "journal editorial report," 3/31/07) </p><p><b> <u>fact: governor (candidate last) has a record of fighting for lower taxes in massachusetts.</u> </b> </p><p><b>income tax cut: governor (candidate last) fought to cut the income tax rate in massachusetts from 5.3% to 5%.</b> (scott greenberger, "tax revenue slowdown in forecast," <em>the boston globe</em>, 12/13/05) </p><p><b>capital gains taxes: governor (candidate last) turned the legislature's $250 million retroactive capital gains tax increase into a $250 million tax refund.</b> (governor (candidate full), remarks at the conservative political action conference, washington, d.c., 3/2/07) </p><p><b>investment tax credit: in november 2003, governor (candidate last) signed an economic stimulus package making the investment tax credit (itc) permanent.</b> (office of the governor, "(candidate last) signs economic stimulus, supplemental budget bills," press release, 11/26/03) </p><p><b>property tax relief: governor (candidate last) proposed and signed legislation providing property tax relief to senior citizens, enabling them to keep their homes.</b> (governor (candidate full), "(candidate last) signs bill to give seniors tax relief," press release, 11/20/05) </p><p><b>sales tax holidays: governor (candidate last) extended sales tax holidays.</b> (michael levenson, "governor drums up business for state's tax-free weekend," <em>the boston globe</em>, 8/12/05)</p></span>



